---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "Quantum Basics — Science";
const updated = "Updated: 2026";
---

<Layout title={title}>
  <article class="page">
    <!-- HERO -->
    <header class="hero">
      <div class="hero-top">
        <a class="back" href="/science">← Back to Science</a>
        <span class="chip chip--physics">PHYSICS</span>
      </div>

      <h1>Quantum Basics</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        Quantum physics is the rulebook for the very small. It doesn’t replace reality with “magic” —
        it replaces our everyday intuition with a more precise description: probabilities, waves,
        and measurement.
      </p>

      <div class="hero-grid">
        <section class="card card--soft">
          <h2 class="hsmall">What you’ll learn</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li>What a <b>quantum state</b> is (and what it isn’t).</li>
            <li>Why probability is <b>built-in</b>, not just “missing information”.</li>
            <li>How <b>measurement</b> changes what you can predict.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card card--ink">
          <p class="quote">
            “Quantum theory doesn’t say reality is random for fun. It says the best possible predictions
            are probabilistic — and that’s been confirmed over and over.”
          </p>
          <p class="meta">{updated}</p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- TL;DR -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>TL;DR</h2>
      <div class="tldr">
        <div class="tldr-item">
          <div class="dot dot--a" aria-hidden="true"></div>
          <div>
            <h3>States are like “recipes” for outcomes</h3>
            <p>A quantum state tells you the probabilities of measurement results.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tldr-item">
          <div class="dot dot--b" aria-hidden="true"></div>
          <div>
            <h3>Waves = probabilities</h3>
            <p>The wave function is not a water wave — it’s a mathematical wave of likelihoods.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tldr-item">
          <div class="dot dot--c" aria-hidden="true"></div>
          <div>
            <h3>Measurement matters</h3>
            <p>What you choose to measure affects what can be known about the system next.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION: What is a quantum state -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>1) Quantum state: the “best possible description”</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        In classical physics, if you know position and speed, you can predict the future exactly (in principle).
        In quantum physics, even with perfect knowledge, predictions are fundamentally probabilistic.
        That full knowledge is encoded in the <b>quantum state</b>.
      </p>

      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="hsmall">Think of it like this</h3>
          <div class="stack">
            <div class="callout">
              <h4>Classical</h4>
              <p>“The ball is exactly here, moving exactly like this.”</p>
            </div>
            <div class="callout">
              <h4>Quantum</h4>
              <p>“If you measure position, here are the probabilities. If you measure momentum, here are those.”</p>
            </div>
            <div class="callout">
              <h4>Not just ignorance</h4>
              <p>
                It’s not merely that we don’t know. The theory itself limits what can be simultaneously definite.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <figure class="figure card">
          <figcaption class="figcap"><b>State → outcomes</b> — probability distribution</figcaption>

          <svg viewBox="0 0 720 360" role="img" aria-label="Probability curve showing where a particle is likely to be found">
            <rect x="0" y="0" width="720" height="360" fill="rgba(245,245,247,1)"/>

            <!-- axes -->
            <line x1="70" y1="280" x2="660" y2="280" stroke="rgba(0,0,0,0.18)" stroke-width="2"/>
            <line x1="70" y1="80" x2="70" y2="280" stroke="rgba(0,0,0,0.18)" stroke-width="2"/>

            <text x="660" y="305" text-anchor="end" font-size="12" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.55)">position</text>
            <text x="75" y="78" font-size="12" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.55)">probability</text>

            <!-- curve -->
            <path
              d="M90 280
                 C160 278, 190 260, 230 235
                 C270 210, 300 140, 360 125
                 C420 110, 470 160, 505 200
                 C540 240, 590 275, 660 280"
              fill="none"
              stroke="rgba(0,122,255,0.95)"
              stroke-width="4"
              stroke-linecap="round"
            />

            <!-- highlighted likely region -->
            <rect x="300" y="100" width="120" height="190" rx="16" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.10)" />
            <text x="360" y="325" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.60)">
              most likely region
            </text>

            <text x="360" y="55" text-anchor="middle" font-size="14" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.70)">
              A quantum state often predicts a range of outcomes, not a single point.
            </text>
          </svg>

          <p class="note">
            The curve doesn’t mean the particle is “smeared like fog” in a classical sense — it means measurements have
            a spread of possible results.
          </p>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION: Wavefunction -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>2) The wave function: a wave of likelihoods</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        The wave function (often written as ψ) is a compact way to store probability information. Where |ψ| is larger,
        you’re more likely to measure the particle there. It evolves smoothly over time — until measurement.
      </p>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="grid3">
          <div class="mini">
            <h4>Not a water wave</h4>
            <p>It’s a mathematical object that produces probabilities.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="mini">
            <h4>Interference is real</h4>
            <p>Probabilities can add or cancel — that’s why double-slit patterns appear.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="mini">
            <h4>Phase matters</h4>
            <p>Hidden “angles” in ψ affect interference even if |ψ| looks the same.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION: Double slit -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>3) The double-slit idea (without the drama)</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        If you send particles through two slits, you get an interference pattern — like waves. If you measure
        “which slit” each particle goes through, the interference disappears. This isn’t because particles “hate”
        being watched; it’s because measurement changes what can remain coherent.
      </p>

      <figure class="figure card">
        <figcaption class="figcap"><b>Interference</b> — waves of probability</figcaption>

        <svg viewBox="0 0 860 320" role="img" aria-label="Double slit diagram showing interference vs no interference when measuring which slit">
          <rect x="0" y="0" width="860" height="320" fill="rgba(245,245,247,1)"/>

          <!-- source -->
          <circle cx="90" cy="160" r="10" fill="rgba(255,45,85,0.92)"/>
          <text x="90" y="135" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.55)">source</text>

          <!-- barrier -->
          <rect x="260" y="60" width="14" height="200" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.18)"/>
          <rect x="274" y="60" width="14" height="200" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.10)"/>
          <!-- slits -->
          <rect x="260" y="120" width="28" height="18" fill="rgba(245,245,247,1)"/>
          <rect x="260" y="182" width="28" height="18" fill="rgba(245,245,247,1)"/>

          <text x="274" y="48" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.55)">slits</text>

          <!-- screen -->
          <rect x="770" y="60" width="18" height="200" rx="9" fill="rgba(0,0,0,0.10)"/>
          <text x="780" y="48" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.55)">screen</text>

          <!-- paths -->
          <path d="M100 160 C160 140, 210 135, 260 130" fill="none" stroke="rgba(255,45,85,0.55)" stroke-width="3"/>
          <path d="M100 160 C160 180, 210 195, 260 190" fill="none" stroke="rgba(255,45,85,0.55)" stroke-width="3"/>

          <!-- wavefront / interference bands on screen (left half label) -->
          <g>
            <rect x="792" y="70" width="46" height="8" rx="4" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.50)"/>
            <rect x="792" y="92" width="46" height="10" rx="5" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.18)"/>
            <rect x="792" y="120" width="46" height="14" rx="7" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.60)"/>
            <rect x="792" y="150" width="46" height="12" rx="6" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.20)"/>
            <rect x="792" y="176" width="46" height="16" rx="8" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.65)"/>
            <rect x="792" y="206" width="46" height="10" rx="5" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.18)"/>
            <rect x="792" y="230" width="46" height="8" rx="4" fill="rgba(0,122,255,0.50)"/>
          </g>

          <text x="520" y="300" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" fill="rgba(11,11,15,0.60)">
            No “which-slit” info → interference. Which-slit measured → interference fades.
          </text>
        </svg>

        <p class="note">
          The key word is <b>coherence</b>: maintaining phase relationships. Measurement (or environment) can destroy coherence.
        </p>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION: Measurement -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>4) Measurement: what changes?</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Measurement forces a specific outcome from a range of possibilities. After measurement, the state updates to match
        what you learned. Practically, this means you can’t keep all “wave-like” relationships once you extract path information.
      </p>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="grid3">
          <div class="mini">
            <h4>Before</h4>
            <p>State encodes multiple possible results.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="mini">
            <h4>During</h4>
            <p>Interaction with measuring device/environment selects an outcome.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="mini">
            <h4>After</h4>
            <p>The state is updated; future predictions depend on the measurement.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Explain to a child -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Explain it to a child</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p class="lead">
          Imagine you have a mystery box that can give different prizes.
        </p>
        <ol class="steps">
          <li>Before opening, the box has chances for different prizes.</li>
          <li>When you open it, you get one prize — and now you know which one.</li>
          <li>Quantum things are like that, but the “chances” can interfere like waves.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="note">
          The box idea is not perfect, but it helps: quantum theory is a rulebook for predicting what you’ll see.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details class="card" open>
          <summary>Is quantum randomness “real”?</summary>
          <p>
            According to standard quantum theory, yes — outcomes are fundamentally probabilistic, not just unknown.
            There are alternative interpretations, but they reproduce the same tested predictions.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="card">
          <summary>Does observation require a human?</summary>
          <p>
            No. “Observation” means interaction that records information (a detector, environment, etc.).
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="card">
          <summary>Why does quantum matter for technology?</summary>
          <p>
            Semiconductors, lasers, MRI, and atomic clocks rely on quantum behavior. Modern computing is built on it.
          </p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FOOT NAV -->
    <nav class="footnav">
      <a class="btn" href="/science/time">← Previous: Time</a>
      <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/science/superposition">Next: Superposition →</a>
    </nav>
  </article>

  <style>
    .page{ max-width: 980px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 28px 18px 90px; }
    .hero{ padding-top: 6px; }
    .hero-top{ display:flex; align-items:center; justify-content: space-between; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 14px; }
    .back{ color: rgba(11,11,15,0.60); font-size: 13px; font-weight: 650; text-decoration: none; }
    .back:hover{ color: rgba(11,11,15,0.90); }

    h1{ margin: 0 0 10px; font-size: 44px; font-weight: 850; letter-spacing: -0.035em; line-height: 1.05; }
    .subtitle{ margin: 0 0 18px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: rgba(11,11,15,0.62); max-width: 78ch; }

    .hero-grid{ display:grid; grid-template-columns: 1.1fr 0.9fr; gap: 14px; margin-top: 16px; }

    .section{ margin-top: 28px; }
    .section > h2{ margin: 0 0 12px; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 850; letter-spacing: -0.02em; color: rgba(11,11,15,0.92); }
    .lead{ margin: 0 0 14px; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: rgba(11,11,15,0.70); max-width: 84ch; }

    .card{
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.92);
      border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.06);
      border-radius: 18px;
      box-shadow: 0 10px 34px rgba(0,0,0,0.06);
      padding: 16px 18px;
    }
    .card--soft{ background: rgba(255,255,255,0.85); }
    .card--ink{
      background: rgba(11,11,15,0.92);
      border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.08);
      color: rgba(255,255,255,0.92);
      box-shadow: 0 12px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.12);
    }
    .quote{ margin: 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.92); }
    .meta{ margin: 12px 0 0; font-size: 12px; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.70); }

    .hsmall{ margin: 0 0 10px; font-size: 13px; font-weight: 900; letter-spacing: .12em; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgba(11,11,15,0.72); }
    .list{ margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; color: rgba(11,11,15,0.72); line-height: 1.65; font-size: 14px; }

    .chip{
      font-size: 11px;
      font-weight: 900;
      letter-spacing: .14em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      padding: 7px 10px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.08);
      user-select: none;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.70);
      backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    }
    .chip--physics{
      color: rgba(0,122,255,0.95);
      border-color: rgba(0,122,255,0.20);
      background: rgba(0,122,255,0.12);
    }

    .tldr{ display:grid; gap: 12px; }
    .tldr-item{
      display:flex; gap: 12px; align-items:flex-start;
      padding: 14px 16px; border-radius: 18px;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.92);
      border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.06);
      box-shadow: 0 10px 34px rgba(0,0,0,0.06);
    }
    .tldr-item h3{ margin: 0 0 4px; font-size: 15px; font-weight: 850; letter-spacing: -0.01em; }
    .tldr-item p{ margin: 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: rgba(11,11,15,0.62); }

    .dot{ width: 10px; height: 10px; border-radius: 999px; margin-top: 5px; flex-shrink:0; }
    .dot--a{ background: rgba(0,122,255,0.95); box-shadow: 0 0 0 4px rgba(0,122,255,0.12); }
    .dot--b{ background: rgba(255,45,85,0.95); box-shadow: 0 0 0 4px rgba(255,45,85,0.12); }
    .dot--c{ background: rgba(52,199,89,0.95); box-shadow: 0 0 0 4px rgba(52,199,89,0.12); }

